Adjust rack to middle position and preheat #oven to 425 degrees. Wash and dry produce.

Melt @Butter{1%tablespoon} in a #small pot{} over medium-high heat. Add @Jasmine Rice{1/2%cup}, 3/4 cup water, and a pinch of @salt{pinch}. Bring to a boil, then cover and reduce to a low simmer. Cook until rice is tender, ~{15-18%minutes}.

Keep covered off heat until ready to use in step 4.

Meanwhile, halve @Bell Pepper{2} lengthwise; remove stems and seeds.

Place bell peppers on a #baking sheet{} and drizzle each half with @Cooking Oil{4%teaspoon}; rub to coat. Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}. Arrange cut sides down. Roast until browned and softened, ~{18-20%minutes}.

Meanwhile, finely dice @Celery{2.5%ounce}. Trim and thinly slice @Scallions{2}, separating whites from greens.

Remove @?pork sausage{} from casing if necessary; discard casing. Heat a drizzle of @Olive Oil{1%teaspoon} in a large, preferably ovenproof, pan over medium-high heat. Add @Ground Turkey{10%ounce} and cook, breaking up meat into pieces, until browned, ~{4-5%minutes}.

Add celery and scallion whites; cook, stirring, until veggies are slightly softened and sausage is cooked through, ~{2-3%minutes}.

Season with @Cajun Spice Blend{1%tablespoon}, salt, and pepper; cook, stirring, until fragrant, ~{30-60%seconds} more.

> Swap in chicken sausage or turkey for pork sausage.

Add @Chicken Stock Concentrate{1} and 1/3 cup water to pan with sausage mixture; simmer, stirring occasionally, until slightly thickened, ~{1-2%minutes}.

Add cooked rice; stir until thoroughly combined. Turn off heat.

Once bell peppers are done, remove from oven. Carefully flip and stuff each half with as much filling as will fit.

Place stuffed peppers in pan with remaining filling, nestling each into mixture.

> TIP: If your pan isn't ovenproof, transfer stuffed peppers and extra filling to a small #baking dish{}.

Evenly sprinkle with @Pepper Jack Cheese{1/2%cup}.

Bake stuffed peppers on middle rack until cheese melts, ~{3-4%minutes}.

Meanwhile, in a #small bowl{}, combine @Sour Cream{1.5%tablespoon} with @Hot Sauce{1%teaspoon} to taste. Add water 1 tsp at a time until mixture reaches a drizzling consistency.

Divide remaining filling between plates and top with stuffed peppers. Drizzle with hot sauce crema and garnish with scallion greens. Serve with any remaining hot sauce on the side.

> Ground Turkey is fully cooked when internal temperature reaches 165°.